description:
&lt;p&gt;An exciting opportunity has arisen within the Haematology Service at University Hospital Southampton NHS Foundation Trust (UHS) for a 9-month maternity cover. This is a part time role working 18.75 hours per week. The post-holder will be working closely with another Anthony Nolan psychologist to offer a psychology service to support patients undergoing stem cell transplantation.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;ABOUT THE TEAM&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The maternity cover is funded by and works in partnership with the Anthony Nolan. It is a part of a three year project developing a pathway for psychological support and offering people support at different points in their transplant journey. The aim of the project is to embed psychological provision within the haematology service and secure longer term funding for the service. As part of the post, the post-holder will work with patients and team members to evaluate the service.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We are a dynamic team of Clinical and Counselling Psychologists that work in different medical services within Southampton University Hospital. The department has close links with Adult and Older Adult Liaison Psychiatry, Neuro-Psychology and Child Health Psychology in University Hospital Southampton.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Within the department there is a keen interest in developing and sharing knowledge. We have active interests in both Systemic, Acceptance and Commitment, EMDR and Cognitive Analytical therapeutic approaches. However, the team also values different approaches and aims to support people developing skills that enable them to work within their specialist areas.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We have close links with Southampton University where there is an established Clinical Psychology training course. There are also specialist courses in Health Psychology and a research group focusing on the applications of Health Psychology.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;WHAT YOU’LL DO&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Aspects of the role include:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Screening and pre-habilitation for transplant&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Working with the P/T Band 7 Psychologist to support patients whilst inpatients.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Developing and offering support post-transplant which includes individual and family interventions and linking into community resources.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Working with the clinical team to support them in the psychological factors around care and their work with patients.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Currently there are two other part time psychologists working in the wider Haematology service and you will work closely together.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The successful post holder will be line managed by the Lead Consultant Clinical Psychologist and supported by other Psychologists working into the wider hospital. You will be responsible to the Lead Nurse Blood and Marrow Transplant. There is a local and national network of Psychologists working in Health and Cancer and you will be encouraged to seek support and take an active role within these groups. You will also have close links to Anthony Nolan.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;WHAT WE’RE LOOKING FOR&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We are looking for an experienced psychologist who enjoys working with teams to offer high quality psychological interventions to patients and support MDT colleagues in their work. You will be interested in gaining feedback from their work and be able to be flexible within their approach. You will have had experience of working in an acute physical setting or working with physical health difficulties.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;WHAT WE CAN OFFER YOU&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As one of the largest acute teaching Trust’s in England, we can offer learning and development opportunities to help you achieve the career you aspire to. We believe you deserve the best possible surroundings in which to do your job and we want to support you in doing your job to the best of your ability.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As a Trust, we support flexible working and will consider requests taking into account the needs of the service. You’ll have an opportunity to discuss this at interview. Our LiveWell and inspire programme offers opportunities, support and advice, including smoking cessation services, exercise and activity classes, and support for mental health.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;UHS employees are able to access a huge range of NHS discounts, are entitled to a minimum of 35 days paid holiday (pro rata) on appointment, can access on-site nursery facilities (subject to availability), and we offer a generous pension scheme.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;ABOUT OUR TRUST AND SOUTHAMPTON&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;UHS is rated ‘Good’ by the CQC and in the latest national NHS Staff Survey, we were in the top 10 acute trusts for staff engagement and for staff recommending the hospital as a place to work or receive care.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Southampton is an attractive place to live and work situated on the south coast, with an international airport and only an hour on the train from central London. The New Forest National Park and the beaches of the Jurassic coast are also right on our doorstep. The city offers living costs 20% lower than those in London, 13 schools rated outstanding by Ofsted and 13 nearby green spaces to enjoy.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;ADDITIONAL INFORMATION&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Interviews will be held on Tuesday 1st December 2020&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For further details / informal visits contact:&lt;/p&gt;
